Overview: The Catapult, though a well-designed BattleMech, has had a tumultuous existence. Produced by Hollis Incorporated in record numbers for the SLDF, the Terran Hegemony ultimately decided to forgo contract renewal, leaving Hollis with a BattleMech line but no customer. When the facility was eventually retooled to produce the BattleMaster, they chose to completely abandon their Catapult chassis, and its numbers began to decline. The attrition of the Succession Wars left the Draconis Combine with many Catapults but no parts for them. Contracting Yori Mech Works, a production line was eventually built and new Catapults began entering the DCMS by 3033. The Capellan Confederation would follow suit and the Catapult would finally claim the popularity that it deserved.

Capabilities: Carrying two LRM launchers in its "ears" and four medium lasers in its body, the Catapult was a fire support 'Mech akin to the slightly larger Archer. The inclusion of jump jets, though, and the placement of the lasers allowed many Catapults to be their own bodyguards. Many Catapult MechWarriors choose to fire all of their LRM missiles at their chosen targets before closing in to exploit any armor breaches with their lasers. This does make the Catapult slightly more flexible than many traditional support 'Mechs, although its limited ammunition stores can hamper it in extended ranged battles.

Deployment: While visible in every military of note, the Capellan Confederation and Draconis Combine would lay claim to the lion's share of the design. When production for the Catapult began in both states, the divide only increased, with many states losing all of their examples of the design by the conclusion of the Jihad. A Kuritan innovation, the CPLT-K2 would replace both LRM "ears" with twin PPCs. This, combined with strengthened armor and twin machine guns, would turn the -K2 into a powerful line 'Mech suited to the Samurai mentality of many Combine MechWarriors. The formation of the Free Rasalhague Republic would see it enter service in the young state as well, though more advanced version of the -K2 would eventually lead to its disappearance.

# Fluff Date: 2026-02-09 16:25:29
overview:<p>The Catapult is a 65-ton fire support BattleMech originally produced by Hollis Incorporated, a Terran Hegemony company that first manufactured the design beginning in 2561. Conceived in anticipation of the Reunification War and debuting during the negotiations that would form the Star League, the Catapult filled the role of a second-line missile support platform capable of punishing enemies at extreme range. Hollis produced the chassis in record numbers across its initial production contract, though the Hegemony chose not to renew the agreement in 2563, deeming the design adequate but not exceptional. The Catapult saw numerous production runs from the late Age of War well into the early Succession Wars, with significant stylistic variations between manufacturing periods including differences in leg length, body profile, and missile port configurations. Though factory losses during the Succession Wars caused increasing scarcity, production was revived in 3033 when Yori 'Mech Works began manufacturing the CPLT-K2 variant on Al Na'ir for the Draconis Combine.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Catapult is primarily a fire-support platform built around a pair of Holly Long Range Missile 15-rack launchers mounted in distinctive pod-like housings flanking the cockpit. These thirty-tube launchers can begin engaging targets at ranges exceeding 600 meters, well before most opponents can effectively respond. When enemies close within the missiles' minimum effective range, four Martell medium lasers mounted below the cockpit provide adequate short-range defense capable of discouraging most light and medium 'Mechs from pressing an engagement. The design's greatest vulnerability lies in its ammunition dependency, carrying only eight reloads per launcher, which makes the Catapult heavily reliant on logistical support during extended operations.</p><p>Ten tons of Durallex Heavy armor provides respectable protection for a fire-support platform, while the Magna 260 fusion engine drives the chassis to a maximum speed of 64 kilometers per hour. Four jump jets grant a 120-meter jumping capability that allows the Catapult to keep pace with faster units across broken terrain. The original Anderson Model 21 jump jets proved prone to breakdowns that vented heat directly into the 'Mech's interior, prompting a general recall in 2656 to replace them with improved Model 25s, though some Catapults never received this retrofit. The lack of arms limits close-quarters capability and leaves the design without anti-infantry weapons, reinforcing the need to maintain standoff distance whenever possible. A distinctive sideways ejection system, while generally considered safe, has been known to surprise pilots unfamiliar with the design.</p>

deployment:<p>The K2 broke the Catapult's fire-support mold entirely, replacing both LRM-15 launchers with twin PPCs to create a direct-fire heavy combatant. Five additional heat sinks were added to help manage the particle cannons' significant thermal output, while two machine guns provided anti-infantry capability the original design had always lacked. To accommodate these changes, the jump jets and two medium lasers were removed, sacrificing mobility and close-range flexibility. Originally a Draconis Combine field refit, the K2 became the first Catapult variant to enter renewed production when Yori 'Mech Works began manufacturing it on Al Na'ir in 3033, serving the Combine well as a front-line direct-fire platform.</p>

history:<p>The Catapult's operational history spans centuries of continuous service across the Inner Sphere. Hollis Incorporated was originally a Terran Hegemony company whose first production run of the Catapult predated the colonization of Corey and the formation of the Star League by nearly a decade. During the Star League era, the design served primarily with second-line and specialist formations, including mountaineering regiments that exploited its jump capability in difficult terrain. When Hollis' primary factory transitioned to BattleMaster production, limited spare parts availability caused operational numbers to gradually decline despite continued manufacturing runs that introduced various stylistic changes to the chassis profile.</p><p>The fall of the Star League marked a turning point for the Catapult. Many operational units accompanied Aleksandr Kerensky on his Exodus, while the Capellan Confederation secured the largest concentration of those remaining in the Inner Sphere. Hollis' factory on Corey briefly resumed production of new frames and spare parts, and the Draconis Combine simultaneously seized a substantial force during their capture of Dieron. The destruction of the Corey facility at the onset of the First Succession War ended renewed production and ensured the Catapult's increasing rarity throughout that devastating conflict. The design became so prized that entire invasions were launched to capture surviving examples, particularly Federated Suns campaigns against the Capellan Confederation.</p><p>The Catapult's scarcity began to reverse in 3033 when Yori 'Mech Works was contracted by the Draconis Combine Mustered Soldiery to restart production on Al Na'ir, initially focusing on the CPLT-K2 variant. This renewed manufacturing capability paved the way for the CPLT-C3, the first BattleMech to mount the newly rediscovered Arrow IV artillery system. Despite a rushed development cycle that reintroduced known deficiencies, the Confederation made excellent use of C3 and Raven tandems, bringing mobile 'Mech-mounted artillery to the forefront of combined-arms doctrine. The far superior O-Bakemono might not exist if not for the C3 paving the way for 'Mech-mounted artillery.</p><p>In the years surrounding the Clan Invasion, the Capellan Confederation and Draconis Combine retained the largest active Catapult formations, though numerous Periphery realms continued to field centuries-old examples. Variant development continued through the FedCom Civil War, the Jihad, and into the Dark Age, with both Hollis Incorporated on Corey and Yori 'Mech Works on Al Na'ir and later Algedi producing new models. The Catapult's proven adaptability across fire-support, direct-fire, and artillery roles has cemented its legacy as one of the Inner Sphere's most enduring heavy BattleMech platforms.</p>

